title: Robot Arm For AX-12A Dynamixel Actuators

description.text: This is a 6 degree of freedom robot arm designed for AX-12A Dynamixel robot actuators.  It's similar to the turtle bot arm.

Things you will need. 6 AX-12A Dynamixel actuators 1 ArbotiX-M Robocontroler You also need six Dynamixel 3 pin cables. 1 100mm cable 5 200mm cables I purchased these from Trossen robotics, the assembly guide for their robot arm Phantom X Pincher
http://www.trossenrobotics.com/productdocs/assemblyguides/phantomx-basic-robot-arm.html
is a good resource as my arm is similar in design. You will need a thrust bearing 35mm x 52mm x 4mm Needle Roller Bearing Thrust Ball Bearing AXK3552 You can buy these off e-bay pretty cheaply. You will also need to get your hands on some RC car wheel bearings the arm uses three, 1 in the elbow 1 in the wrist and 1 in the shoulder joint. measurements of these are 5x11x4mm you should also be able to purchase these pretty easily on e-Bay. Nuts and bolts, I've added some extras because it is very easy to lose these tiny screws. 40 M2 x 8 12 M2 x 10 4 M3 x 10 40 M2 nuts Of the 3-D printed parts You will need to print one of each of the following base_legs_arbotix_m.stl
base_turn_table_bot.stl

The top part is made from two component molding silicone, but any similar rubber or silicone substance can be used. Mold consists of 2 parts that go together to form the whole. It might be nessesary to drill a hole in the top to be able to pour silicone in. You can also fill two parts seperately and then squeeze them together. Beware of the air bubbles when pouring.

description.text:
This is a print bed bracket for the Skeleton-3d. This allows you to clip a sheet of glass to a spring-mounted platform... this is needed especially if you don't have a PCB bed heater to clip onto.

Also, if you're looking into attaching a 100x100mm silicone pad to your glass... then I recommend editing the bracket's SCAD to remove the grid. It should be out of the way and the heating pad should clear the platform!

Currently I'm using this with PLA on a PEI sheet that I cut with a box cutter. Works okay so far. Mounted on a 4.5"x4.5" glass sheet I got from Lowes.

The corner brackets allow you to have a nut trap to hold it still while you adjust the bed from above with a screw driver. This wraps around the corners of the wood piece that you cut and drill for the print bed. Edit the SCAD file to the appropriate thickness of the wood plank that you used.

Enjoy! I hope this is useful to some of you!!!

description.text:
This is a model I recreated from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7579 I wanted to make some changes and put in a hollow recess to fit a servo and servo horn. I used Google Sketchup to build the torso from scratch. I also used it to create the servo horn recess at the top of the legs. Because of the way sketchup works, the imported stl files for legs and arms from thing:7579 have tiny holes in the geometry. I made my changes and then used http://cloud.netfabb.com/ to fill in the holes and output a printable stl file. I have attached all my google sketchup designs and the stl files ready to print. I printed this on an UP 3d printer, as you can see in the main pic. The servo recess fits a standard micro servo that you can buy on ebay for about $3 I did make the arms and body to have a small indent to glue in magnets to hold the arms in place but the weight of the arms makes the arms drop. Perhaps they can be repositioned or made larger. Servo:

description.text: Anyone who plays with a B9C knows how messy it is to empty the VAT after a failed print or to change the resin yet I couldn't find a printable spout to ease this operation... description.text:
These are the brackets needed to make an enclosure for your rostock max v2. You will need 3 base and 3 top pieces. You can print 3 at a time with the build area.

Locate the brackets on the extrusions and bolt the brackets to the rostock's top and base using 6-32x.75" bolts with nuts (M3 x20mm bolts will work too). You will need to drill holes in your printer. I used one sheet of 36" x 48" x .093" acrylic http://www.homedepot.com/p/OPTIX-36-in-x-48-in-x-093-in-Acrylic-Sheet-MC-09/202038045
and one piece of 1/8" x 12" x 36" acrylic for the door. Cut all sheets to 29" in length with a plastic scraping cutter or saw and cut the .093" sheet into 3-6" widths and 2-12" widths for the enclosure sides. All hardware is 1/4-20 nyloc nuts and 1/4-20 x 7/8" SHCS, but I would recommend 1" length bolts since mine didn't reach the nylon in the nuts, but it was what I already had in my garage. I sealed the case with silicone and foam tape on the seams to try and eliminate all gaps for the best insulation. For the door I just bought door hinges at the depot and I used a soldering iron for all holes in the acrylic because it cracks very easily with a standard drill.

You will need this layer fan mount to clear the enclosure when printing towards the extents of the build plate: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1700221

I used this 40mm mount to cool the extruder stepper: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1705843
I wired the 40mm fan to a rocker switch next to the one I use for my lights and used the X-axis extrusion to run a pair of 20ga wires down for the fan.

If you want to illuminate your cabinet, here is the rocker switch box I modeled: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1421639 and here are the extrusion mounts for the LED strips: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1702064

description.text:
This is yet another solution to the occasional problem with the Sigma printer bowden tube creeping out of the hot-end. I modified a previous creator's post to reduce the amount of plastic and amount of supports, but it was such a design as to suggest a weakening of the bowden tube. It also required to calibrate the printer each time the tube was removed and replaced. Too much work!

I recently added (probably inappropriately) to that Thingy a metal shim to replace the threaded fitting:

description.text:
1-7-2017:
New file added for bltouch support. Same rigid mount, just with a bltouch mount instead.

10-6-2016:
I've been able to print the latest changes and im extremely satisfied with the results.
I have changed up the tie downs a bit to add some more clearance. I even made some (untested) models with the HicWic universal mount in mind. If anyone wants to try them out. Enjoy :)

NOTE:
I've made some improvements to the design, to add better printability. i rounded off the edges of the probe holder, so it wont cut me anymore :)
I reduced the size of the internal duct work and rounded off the internal corners to help it print better and support itself. I thinned down the motor mount wall just enough so those last few screw treads will be able to grab and added some nut slots for the probe holder. I havent actually printed this one yet, but i noticed some uptake in the interest for this part and wanted to get it out there.

I like the original mk mount just fine, but i find it bulky to add the fan and long shroud, and if you need a bed probe then you have to find some way to hang it off of everything. My part adds rigidity, and moves the part fan into the mount itself, and it works very well, forcing air through the mount and out the bottom directly to the nozzle. there is a sleeve for the standard chinese capacitive bed level probe which is larger than the standard inductive probe. if you need to use an inductive probe then you could print a sleeve for it to slide into this mount. this is just the first go at this design, i have plans to tweak the design a bit more, I was skeptical at first as to if it would print at all, but my MPCNC has no problems with bridging and overhangs. some slicers have the ability to selectively add supports manually, but so far i havent needed any supports, just a bit of extra cleanup so the fan fits snugly. feel free to make suggestions, as this is my first real attemp at cad design using more than tinkercad. I only used tinkercad to do some testing and to add the mount geometry easily.

https://youtu.be/Wei3ACiulS4

description.text:
A sink stopper. A minor thing really. But I lost mine.

It was Italian. A work of beauty that had a perfect union with the sink hole. After many an aftermarket stoppers were summarily rejected by the prudish Italian sink hole for being too big, too small, or simply mismatched on their interference plane I set on a quest to design a "perfect" sink stopper.

Unfortunately, there are no compendiums or seminal anthologies on sink stoppers. No "Sink Stopper Research Bulletin". No "Sink Stoppers 6th Edition" for $389 + S&H published by Addison Wesley. No. Zilch.

This is like Sushi - family secrets of sink stopper designs. I am on my own.

3 courageous attempts it took to conquer the stopper mountain. It wasn't easy.

Attempt 1: A "plug" with knob. Left most stopper in the picture.
Easy to use. Since sink hole isn't 100% round - it doesn't seal nor stay put.
Worse, it is hollow so it floats. It seems sink stoppers are supposed to stay at the bottom of the sink. I suppose I could fill 100% and print using NinjaFlex - but I use a Bowden...

Attempt 2: Hollow from top. Water pushes stopper down. Middle stopper in the picture.
Yay. Seal is okay but some leakage occurs. Interference angle with sink hole is finicky.

Final attempt: Outrageous success (Yay). Right most stopper in the picture.
Rounding the mating surfaces means the sidewalls are thinner, enabling the water pushing down to force the stopper into a full seal. Just enough compliance to force a fit between the stopper and the sink hole. It seals really well!!!

Additional features: Indented knob ensures that cloths being manually laundered don't pry the stopper accidentally. Knob is also tapered making it easy to lift even with soapy water/hands.

It works really well.

Saga over.

Aftermath: 3 YO finds stopper and says "Oh Red". Stopper is gone again. Next version is tethered.

Print movie: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2AWSphQ6Amo

RepRap

Printer:

Kossel Mini

No

No

Honeycomb?

Notes:

I used soft PLA. 230 degree on a 50 degree bed. Slow makes soft work even with Bowden. So 20mm/Sec makes it as easy as it is slow to print...

Since your hole will be different than mine you will need a different plug to seal it. Hence I added the OpenSCAD files for you to mess with.

title: Z nut retainer for MakerFarm Prusa i3

description.text:
I had a problem where the nuts on the Z axis threaded rods came "unseated" from the hex hole in the X idler and X motor housings.  
This is my solution.

This needs printed with the wide part at the top (upside-down) to avoid a 90 degree overhang.  So you'll need to rotate it 180° before you slice it.  
It is installed with the narrow end up; it fits into the hex hole where the nut is; the flanged end provides the "stop" to prevent any movement of the nut relative to the wood housing.  
The hole running the length of the part is smaller than the diameter of the Z threaded rod because I couldn't get a good print with the walls that thin.  
So, after printing, you'll need to drill out the hole so that it slides easily over the Z threaded rod.  (So use ABS, not PLA; PLA is too brittle, and will snap apart).  
Due to the proximity of the screws holding the motor side together and the Z threaded rod, I had to notch the part to allow room for the assembly screws. (see photos).

title: ATX power connector bracket (shown on MakerFarm Prusa i3)

description.text:
Update 2/24/2014
I needed to replace the extensions I originally used (they were too cheap; the wire gauge used was way too thin). So, when I got new ones, I decided it was time to redesign this thing a bit. The new file is the "ATX power plug bracket.stl".

  • The openings are enlarged slightly so the connectors should just snap in right off the printer; no cleanup necessary. This was the primary reason for updating the design; I had to do a fair amount of cleanup/scraping to the original part to get the connectors to fit.

  • It's a bit longer, so the mounting ears could be moved outward a bit, so that you can get at the mounting screws while the (printer-side) connectors are still in the bracket.

  • The mounting ears are thicker/stronger, and the printed screw holes are slightly larger (you'll probably still need to drill them out to match the screws you use).
    • I left the original files there in case you need the tighter tolerance.

Rather than cut off the connectors on the power supply to connect to the circuit board, I got a couple of ATX extension cables from Amazon, and cut those.  
Then I printed a bracket to rigidly mount them to the printer; now the power supply can be easily plugged/unplugged from the printer.

There are two dimples in the center of the mounting tabs to aid in drilling holes for your mounting screws.  
The tolerances on the holes are very tight, and at least in my case, I don't get very sharp inside corners on prints, so there was some carving with a knife required to get the connectors to snap in.

A gear bearing inspired from Emmet's. It operates on the same premise, but whereas his uses herringbone geared rolling elements, mine uses geared rollers with conical ends. This results in a more sealed design, one that is a bit easier to print, and (I think) it can tolerate more axial loading. The design still needs to be refined, so a couple drops of oil can make it run smoother. No OpenScad version yet.

comments.text: I tried something similar, minus the gearing. With the model finished in OpenSCAD, the STL exported, and being sliced, I started thinking about the conical bearings. The problem is that the part of the cone with a larger radius fights the part with a smaller radius and generates friction. Since Emmit's design is hardly friction-free, your design may actually be an improvement, but mine wouldn't have been.

Notes:

Please, refer to Cool PS Enclosure for printing tips.

Version 1.0:

  • 1 PS module at the bottom shield.
  • Up to 4 PCB modules at the bottom and/or 3 at the top.
  • Customizable Fan grid (bottom, top or rear).
  • Customizable number of screws per side (on reeds).
  • Pegs and anti-pegs on the edges.
  • Honeycomb mesh for shield reinforcement and lightness.
  • Corner reinforcements.
  • Up to 6 vertical pillars (very useful for large boxes).
  • Split shield into smaller parts (very useful for easy printing of large boxes).
  • Snowflake shaped ventilation hole.

Notes when using the Customizer App

  • The coordinate system is mostly center based in order to simplify the integration between different projects involved.

  • Fan grille's logos cannot be used through the Customizer App.
    In order to customize Fan grille's logos, you must download both source code files and use Openscad instead.

  • Please, verify the plug hole dimensions printing the following rounded poligon first.

Hacking the source code

The source code is the result of the integration of the following excellent projects:

  • The Ultimate box maker
  • Customizable Fan Grille
  • Openscad hex grid generator

Please, refer to these original projects for additional documentation and samples.

OpenSCAD source file is also freely available at this URL:
https://github.com/valba/Cool_PCB_Enclosure

Some customizations:
  • SL Power GPC130BG
